---
title: Visualizing survival
guide-section: "Estimation"
bread-crumbs: false
---



A survival curve is far easier to understand as a picture than as a table of numbers. By default
Greenwood draws curves with [Altair](https://altair-viz.github.io/), which produces interactive
charts (tooltips and zoom) and is Narwhals-native: the numbers flow straight from your Polars fit
into the chart with no Pandas or Matplotlib in the way, so a pure Polars/Narwhals workflow stays
that way. This page covers the survival curve plot, confidence bands, censoring marks, and the
numbers-at-risk table.

Altair is an optional dependency. If you installed Greenwood with the `altair` extra, or with
`all`, you already have it. We use the `lung` dataset throughout. First we build the response.

::: {#8c8d929a .cell execution_count=2}
``` {.python .cell-code}
import greenwood as gw

# Load the bundled lung dataset as a Polars DataFrame
lung = gw.load_dataset("lung", backend="polars")

# Build a right-censored response; status == 2 marks a death
y = gw.Surv.right(lung["time"], event=(lung["status"] == 2))

# Display the response summary
y
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=2}
```
Surv(type=right, n=228, events=165)
```
:::
:::


We then fit a Kaplan-Meier estimator stratified by sex, one curve per group, using the log-log
confidence interval transform. Printing the fitted estimator summarizes each stratum.

::: {#decb2289 .cell execution_count=3}
``` {.python .cell-code}
# Fit Kaplan-Meier with log-log CI transform, stratified by sex
km = gw.KaplanMeier(conf_type="log-log").fit(y, by=lung["sex"])

# Print per-stratum median survival
km
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=3}
```
KaplanMeier (Kaplan-Meier survival estimate)

     n  events  median  0.95LCL  0.95UCL
1  138     112     270      210      306
2   90      53     426      345      524
```
:::
:::


Everything below draws from this fitted `km` object. Before plotting, it also helps to see the
numbers the curve is built from. Calling `to_frame()` on the fitted estimator returns the
step-function estimates in tidy form, one row per stratum and time, with the survival probability
and its confidence limits. The preview shows the first and last rows along with the full dimensions
of the table.

::: {#7686e742 .cell execution_count=4}
``` {.python .cell-code}
# Export the step-function estimates as a tidy DataFrame (one row per stratum and time)
km.to_frame(format="polars")
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=4}
